Technical Workflow: Step-by-Step Implementation
Step 1: Virtual Environment Setup
Hypervisor Deployment: Installed and configured Oracle VM VirtualBox as the base hypervisor platform.

Virtual Machine Provisioning: Provisioned three isolated virtual instances:

Firewall/Gateway: Assigned 4 vCPUs and 4 GB RAM to host the pfSense OS.

Client Instance: Configured an OS instance to generate regular simulated user traffic.

Attacker Instance: Set up an offensive system equipped with network scanning and stress-testing software.

Step 2: Virtual Network Configuration
Interface Mapping: Built a secure multi-interface topology to process traffic segments safely:

WAN (External): Configured as a Bridged/NAT adapter connected directly to the physical host’s uplink network.

LAN (Internal): Created an isolated, non-routable Internal Network subnet (192.168.1.1/24) connecting the firewall securely to the Client node.

DMZ (Optional Peripheral): Mapped an additional subnet to host public-facing services if needed.

Step 3: pfSense Firewall Setup & Traffic Engineering
Core Configuration: Deployed and scripted pfSense settings to act as the primary security boundary.

Access Control Policies (ACLs): Scripted and enforced foundational firewall rules:

An explicit Pass rule allowing authorized protocol traffic outbound from the internal LAN to any destination.

A restrictive Block rule to drop unsolicited external ICMP packets arriving over the WAN interface.

Outbound Translation: Implemented Automatic Outbound Network Address Translation (NAT) so internal LAN nodes can access the external WAN.

Step 4: Suricata Engine Integration (IDS Mode)
Package Provisioning: Installed the stable Suricata threat detection package directly into the system pipeline.

Rule Engine Activation: Hooked Suricata into threat feeds (Emerging Threats Open Ruleset) and initialized updates via the global management interface.

Traffic Interception: Assigned Suricata to bind to designated network interfaces to sniff and perform deep packet inspection.

Traffic Bypass Tuning: Enabled the option to bypass scrutiny for trusted internal traffic navigating the same local interface to keep packet processing optimized.

Step 5: Transition to Real-Time Prevention (IPS Mode)
Mitigation Activation: Shifted Suricata from a passive monitoring tool to an active protection layer by checking Block Offenders in the interface properties.

Category Enforcement: Hand-selected and activated strict defensive signatures targeting malicious traffic patterns (dos.rules and emerging-dos.rules).

Custom Signature Creation: Structured dedicated threshold rules directly inside the custom configuration field to intercept fine-grained patterns, including SYN, ACK, RST, UDP floods, and Ping of Death anomalies.

Step 6: Attack Simulation, Logging, and Validation
Launching the Attack Vector: Used the Low Orbit Ion Cannon (LOIC) utility on the Attacker VM to generate heavy, continuous TCP/UDP/HTTP request streams toward the internal targets.

Telemetry Verification:

Checked pfSense State logs under Diagnostics > States to actively observe the incoming volumetric traffic anomaly.

Monitored Suricata alerts file (alerts.log) to confirm that signatures successfully identified the anomalous connection rates.

Automatic Dropping Verification: Confirmed that Suricata automatically dropped traffic from offending IPs without degrading normal internal communications or generating false positives.
